title: For Sale:  Sig 9mm P250C Slide, Barrel, Grip and Mag Floorplate
postcontent:
If you are familiar with the P250, you're already aware that it is the Mr. Potato Head of handguns.  You can make the pistol into a full size, compact or subcompact.  You can make it a .45, 40, .357 Sig, 9mm, or .380.   Best of all, it is a Sig to its core.  It is solid, well designed and accurate. In the late 80's, I fired an early DAO pistol from another company and immediately swore I would never own one.  The P250 changed my mind in 10 rounds.

You can put a compact slide on a subcompact frame and make a really good sized carry gun. 

I have other parts for the P250 and if you have a fire-control module, I have an entire gun worth of parts for you to build a pistol around.  I even have a spare old-style floorplate and a digital camo grip module that was cut down by a previous owner so it would fit a subcompact slide.  It does still fit the compact slide without looking ungainly.  The rail on the old style grips is not standard, so it won't take regular accessories, but I found it much less likely to snag on the holster.

I can send photos of this selection as a completed gun on my Fire Control Module, but this sale WILL NOT INCLUDE the FCM at this price.  If I have not sold the subcompact pistol, we can make a deal, though.  

I'm  open to trades, but I prefer to trade up.  I can add cash, .999 silver or reloading powder.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Savage Model 99 in .300 Savage - 1926 Takedown
postcontent:
$600/OBO

1926 Savage in the rare Takedown configuration. This rifle has a removable barrel to allow for storage in a pack. The rifle features a rotary internal magazine with built in round counter visible on the side of the receiver.

Rifle is in perfect working order and could be used for hunting immediately if desired. Rifle has some surface rust on one side of the receiver and barrel. Stock has minor damage at the buttstock.

For hunting North American game the Savage 99 is still one of the finest hunting rifles of all time. In fact, it was a solid performer well into the later part of the last century, nearly one hundred years after its creation. It was manufactured for nearly a century with over a million rifles produced before the Savage 99 was discontinued due to decrepit machinery and increased cost.

The design of the 99 is superior to lever actions such as the Winchester 94 and the Marlin 336, because it can handle high intensity cartridges. It has several superior design features that make it more comparable to the Browning BLR and even modern bolt actions like the Winchester Model 70. The rotary spool magazine allows for the use of pointed bullets, which retain greater velocity downrange than the flat point bullets required by lever guns with tubular magazines. Its strong action allowed it to be chambered in many modern, short-action, high intensity cartridges.

For a rifle designed in the last decade of the 1800's, it had many modern day features that are still prevalent on currently produced rifles. It has a cocking indicator on top of the tang and it ejected spent cartridges at an angle, which made it easily adaptable to the use of telescopic sights.

postcontent: This is a Browning FN Hi-Power MK I* semi-automatic pistol chambered in 9mm. It was made in either 1944 or 1945 by John Inglis and Company of Toronto, Canada. The serial number on gun includes the letters “CH” which mean this gun was made to fulfill a Nationalist Chinese contract. It features a 4 ¾” ‘in the white’ barrel, a parkerized slide and frame, an adjustable tangent rear sight, a ring hammer stamped “II”, a manual safety located on the left side of the slide, a magazine disconnect, and checkered wood grips. Also featured is a milled cut in the backstrap to accommodate a removable shoulder stock. This World War Two pistol is in good condition and it appears to have been refinished.

title: For Trade:  Rare Colt M1911 A1 1943 National Match
postcontent:
RARE Colt M1911 A1 early model national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1943 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped to Springfield Armory in February of 1943. It was Issued to an enlisted serviceman at the time. (Trying to find out who it was issued to now through different channels.) There are specific clues on the gun that tell you who it MIGHT have gone to.. There is AA inscribed (Not stamped) on the ivory grips and on the frame Next to GHD. GHD is significant because Col. Guy H. Drewry inspected ordnance from June 17, 1942 to July 15, 1945 For COLT.

After having multiple collectors and Colt dealers at the gun show look at it. "AA" is believed to stand for "All American" 82nd Airborne. Which would match the dates the gun was issued, and the eagle carved on the Ivory grips. 82 Airborne was the first Airborne division in US Army history and had three major drops, made their first drop in July of 1943 to invade Sicily. Second was Salerno on 13 September 1943. The third was the invasion of Normandy Jun 1944.

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. But not all pistols back then were stamped with "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted national match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by a gunsmith. At some point it was re-blued, and fixtures were 24k gold plated and Ivory grips added. It has been determined the gold was added many many years ago as some has worn off in spots. Bluing and finish is still very nice... Bore is excellent and looks shinning.

This pistol is a shooter. I have put 100 rounds through it and drives tacks. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection.

I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. All reasonable offers considered. Email if interested. Will trade multiple guns.. Please list your offer and values of guns. email or text 918-four02-zero854.
